# 🔐 SecureVPC-HA-Infrastructure

> *"Hidden in Private Subnets. Guarded by Bastion. Scaled by AWS."*

**Designed & Deployed by Yogeshvaran Thirugnanamurthy**

---

## 📌 Project Overview

A production-ready, highly available, and secure AWS VPC infrastructure built from scratch. This project demonstrates real-world cloud architecture used by companies to run scalable web applications with zero single point of failure.

The infrastructure ensures:
- 🔒 **Security** — Servers hidden in private subnets, accessible only via Load Balancer
- ⚡ **High Availability** — Resources spread across 2 Availability Zones
- 📈 **Auto Scaling** — Automatically adds/removes servers based on CPU usage
- 🛡️ **Controlled Access** — Bastion Host for secure SSH into private servers

---

## 🏗️ Architecture

```
                        INTERNET
                            |
                    Internet Gateway
                            |
                 Application Load Balancer
                (prod-alb-sg: HTTP 80/443)
                    /              \
         us-east-2a                  us-east-2b
              |                          |
       PUBLIC SUBNET 1            PUBLIC SUBNET 2
       10.0.1.0/24                 10.0.2.0/24
       [NAT Gateway 1]             [NAT Gateway 2]
       [ALB Node]                  [ALB Node]
              |                          |
       PRIVATE SUBNET 1           PRIVATE SUBNET 2
       10.0.3.0/24                 10.0.4.0/24
       [EC2 Server 1]  ←ASG→  [EC2 Server 2]
       
       BASTION HOST (prod-public-subnet-1)
       Secure SSH jump server
```

---

## 🧩 AWS Services Used

| Service | Name | Purpose |
|---------|------|---------|
| VPC | `prod-vpc` | Isolated private network (10.0.0.0/16) |
| Subnets | 4 subnets | 2 public + 2 private across 2 AZs |
| Internet Gateway | `prod-igw` | Internet access for public subnets |
| NAT Gateway | `prod-nat-gw-1/2` | Outbound internet for private servers |
| Route Tables | `prod-public-rt` / `prod-private-rt` | Traffic routing rules |
| Security Groups | `prod-alb-sg` / `prod-ec2-sg` | Firewall rules |
| EC2 (Bastion) | `prod-bastion-host` | Secure jump server |
| Launch Template | `prod-launch-template` | EC2 blueprint for ASG |
| Auto Scaling Group | `prod-asg` | Auto-manages server count (min:2, max:4) |
| Load Balancer | `prod-alb` | Distributes traffic across private EC2s |
| Target Group | `prod-tg` | Health-checked pool of EC2 instances |

---

## 🔒 Security Design

### Security Groups
| Group | Inbound Rule | Purpose |
|-------|-------------|---------|
| `prod-alb-sg` | HTTP 80, HTTPS 443 from 0.0.0.0/0 | ALB accepts public traffic |
| `prod-ec2-sg` | HTTP 80 from `prod-alb-sg` only | EC2 only reachable via ALB |
| `prod-ec2-sg` | SSH 22 from My IP | SSH only from trusted IP |

### Network Architecture
- ✅ EC2 servers have **no public IP** — completely hidden
- ✅ Only the **Load Balancer** is internet-facing
- ✅ Private servers access internet via **NAT Gateway** (outbound only)
- ✅ SSH access only through **Bastion Host**

---

## ⚡ Auto Scaling Configuration

| Setting | Value |
|---------|-------|
| Desired capacity | 2 instances |
| Minimum capacity | 2 instances |
| Maximum capacity | 4 instances |
| Scaling policy | Target tracking — CPU at 50% |
| Health check | EC2 + ELB health checks |
| Warmup period | 300 seconds |

**How it works:**
- CPU > 50% → ASG automatically adds servers (up to 4)
- CPU < 50% → ASG removes extra servers (down to 2)
- Unhealthy server detected → ASG replaces it automatically

---

## 🗺️ Network Configuration

| Resource | CIDR / AZ | Type |
|----------|-----------|------|
| VPC | 10.0.0.0/16 | - |
| Public Subnet 1 | 10.0.1.0/24 · us-east-2a | Public |
| Public Subnet 2 | 10.0.2.0/24 · us-east-2b | Public |
| Private Subnet 1 | 10.0.3.0/24 · us-east-2a | Private |
| Private Subnet 2 | 10.0.4.0/24 · us-east-2b | Private |

---

## 💻 EC2 User Data Script

The following script is used in the Launch Template to auto-configure EC2 instances:

```bash
#!/bin/bash
yum update -y
yum install -y httpd
systemctl start httpd
systemctl enable httpd

EC2_AZ=$(curl -s http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/placement/availability-zone)
EC2_ID=$(curl -s http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/instance-id)

cat > /var/www/html/index.html <<EOF
<!-- Custom dark neon webpage showing Instance ID, AZ, and project info -->
EOF
```

---

## 🔄 Traffic Flow

```
User Request
    ↓
Internet Gateway
    ↓
Application Load Balancer (public subnet)
    ↓
Target Group health check
    ↓
EC2 in private subnet (AZ1 or AZ2)
    ↓
Response back to user ✅

Private EC2 needs internet (updates):
    ↓
NAT Gateway (public subnet)
    ↓
Internet (outbound only) 🔒
```

---

## 🎯 Problems This Architecture Solves

| Problem | Solution |
|---------|----------|
| Server crashes | ASG auto-replaces unhealthy instances |
| Traffic spike | ASG scales up to 4 servers automatically |
| Direct server attack | Servers in private subnets — no public access |
| Single AZ failure | Resources in 2 AZs — other AZ keeps running |
| Overloaded server | ALB distributes traffic evenly |
| Maintenance access | Bastion Host for secure SSH |

---

## 🌐 Output

After deployment, the Load Balancer DNS provides a live webpage showing:
- Project name: **SecureVPC-HA-Infrastructure**
- Live Instance ID
- Live Availability Zone (changes on refresh — proves load balancing works!)
- Infrastructure status

